  "summary": "Drafts a comprehensive, legally compliant Notice of Annual Shareholders Meeting for US corporations, incorporating jurisdictional requirements, record dates, and governance details from bylaws. Ensures clear communication of meeting details, voting rights, and agenda to enable effective shareholder participation. Use this skill when preparing notices for annual meetings to meet statutory notice periods and best practices.",
  "content": "# Notice of Annual Shareholders Meeting - Enhanced Legal Workflow Prompt\n\nYou are tasked with drafting a comprehensive Notice of Annual Shareholders Meeting that complies with all applicable corporate law requirements and serves as legally sufficient notice to all shareholders of record. This document must satisfy statutory notice requirements, adhere to corporate governance best practices, and provide clear, actionable information that enables shareholders to exercise their voting rights effectively.\n\n## Initial Information Gathering and Jurisdictional Analysis\n\nBegin by gathering essential information about the corporation and its governance structure. Search through any uploaded corporate documents to identify the company's full legal name, state of incorporation, current bylaws, articles of incorporation, and any prior meeting notices that may serve as templates. Determine whether the company is publicly traded or closely held, as this fundamentally affects disclosure obligations under federal securities laws. Identify the specific notice period required by the jurisdiction's corporate code, which typically ranges from ten to sixty days depending on the state, and verify any special requirements in the company's governing documents that may impose stricter standards than statutory minimums. Review the bylaws carefully to understand quorum requirements, voting thresholds for different types of resolutions, and any provisions regarding virtual or hybrid meetings.\n\n## Establishing the Legal Framework and Record Date\n\nThe notice must explicitly reference the legal authority under which it is issued, typically citing both the corporation's bylaws and the applicable state business corporation act. Determine the appropriate record date for establishing which shareholders are entitled to notice and voting rights, ensuring it complies with statutory requirements regarding how far in advance of the meeting the record date must be set. The record date determination is critical because it fixes the list of shareholders who will receive notice and be permitted to vote, and it must be clearly communicated in the notice to avoid confusion about eligibility. Consider whether the corporation has multiple classes of stock with different voting rights, as this will require detailed explanation of the voting power associated with each class and any special approval requirements for particular agenda items.\n\n## Drafting the Formal Notice Header and Opening Statement\n\nCreate a formal header that prominently displays \"NOTICE OF ANNUAL MEETING OF SHAREHOLDERS\" along with the corporation's complete legal name exactly as it appears in the articles of incorporation. The opening paragraph should serve as the formal notice statement, explicitly informing all shareholders of record as of the specified record date that the annual meeting will be held and that they are entitled to participate and vote. This opening must convey the legal significance of the notice while remaining accessible to shareholders who may not be familiar with corporate formalities. Include the date of notice issuance and confirm that it falls within the required notice period, as premature or late notice can invalidate meeting actions.\n\n## Comprehensive Meeting Logistics and Accessibility\n\nProvide complete details regarding the meeting format, date, time, and location with sufficient specificity that shareholders can participate without confusion. For in-person meetings, include the full street address, building name, floor, room number, parking information, and any security or access procedures that attendees should anticipate. For virtual meetings, specify the technology platform being used, provide the complete access URL, list any meeting identification codes or passwords, detail technical requirements such as browser compatibility or software downloads, and explain any pre-registration procedures that must be completed before the meeting. If the corporation is conducting a hybrid meeting that allows both in-person and virtual participation, clearly explain how shareholders can choose their preferred method of attendance and ensure that virtual participants will have equivalent opportunities to ask questions and vote. Include contingency language addressing the board's authority to change the meeting format or location due to unforeseen circumstances, such as public health emergencies or technical failures, and specify how shareholders will be notified of such changes through the corporation's website, email, or other communication channels.\n\n## Detailed Agenda with Context for Informed Voting\n\nPresent a comprehensive agenda that itemizes every matter to be brought before shareholders for consideration, providing sufficient context to enable informed decision-making. The standard annual meeting agenda includes the election of directors to serve on the board, with specific identification of the number of board seats to be filled, the term length for each position, and whether directors are elected individually or as a slate. Include the presentation and approval of audited financial statements for the prior fiscal year, noting where shareholders can access the complete financial reports and any management discussion and analysis. Address the ratification of the independent auditor appointment for the current fiscal year, identifying the accounting firm and providing information about their tenure and fees. If any amendments to the articles of incorporation or bylaws are proposed, provide a clear summary of the changes and their implications for shareholder rights, with reference to the full text of proposed amendments in accompanying proxy materials. Include a catch-all provision for \"such other business as may properly come before the meeting,\" while noting that shareholders should not expect substantive matters to be introduced without prior notice. For each agenda item requiring shareholder approval, reference the accompanying proxy statement or information statement that contains detailed background, board recommendations, and any required disclosures under securities laws.\n\n## Voting Rights, Proxy Procedures, and Participation Mechanisms\n\nClearly articulate the record date and explain that only shareholders who owned shares as of the close of business on that specific date are entitled to receive notice and vote at the meeting, even if they subsequently transfer their shares. Detail the voting rights associated with each class of outstanding stock, including the number of votes per share and any special voting provisions such as class voting requirements for particular proposals. Provide comprehensive instructions for shareholders who wish to vote by proxy rather than attending the meeting, including the deadline by which proxies must be received to be counted, the acceptable methods for submitting proxies such as mail, telephone, or internet voting, and where shareholders can obtain official proxy forms if they have not received them. Explain that shareholders who submit proxies retain the right to revoke them at any time before the vote by submitting a later-dated proxy, providing written notice of revocation to the corporate secretary, or attending the meeting and voting in person. If the corporation is subject to SEC proxy rules under Section 14(a) of the Securities Exchange Act, ensure the notice complies with Regulation 14A and references the availability of the proxy statement, which must be furnished to shareholders entitled to vote. Address the quorum requirement by specifying the percentage or number of shares that must be present in person or by proxy to constitute a valid meeting, and explain the vote threshold required for approval of each type of proposal, distinguishing between matters requiring a simple majority, supermajority, or plurality vote.\n\n## Administrative Details and Shareholder Resources\n\nConclude the notice with practical information that enables shareholders to exercise their rights and obtain additional information. Provide complete contact information for the corporate secretary or investor relations officer who can respond to inquiries about the meeting, voting procedures, proxy materials, or corporate governance matters, including a telephone number with business hours, email address, and mailing address. Explain how shareholders can access the annual report, proxy statement, and any other meeting materials, whether through the corporation's website, the SEC's EDGAR database for public companies, or by requesting paper copies from the corporate secretary. If the corporation has adopted notice and access procedures under SEC rules, explain how shareholders can elect to receive paper copies of proxy materials rather than accessing them online. Include a statement regarding the corporation's commitment to accessibility and accommodations for shareholders with disabilities, providing contact information for requesting assistance such as sign language interpreters, assistive listening devices, or accessible meeting formats. For public companies, reference the availability of the annual report on Form 10-K and note that it is incorporated by reference into the proxy statement.\n\n## Execution, Certification, and Distribution Requirements\n\nThe notice must be executed by an authorized officer, typically the corporate secretary or assistant secretary, with a signature block that includes their printed name, title, and the date of execution. The execution date should reflect the actual date the notice is issued and must fall within the statutorily required notice period before the meeting date. Ensure that the completed notice will be distributed to all shareholders of record through the corporation's chosen delivery method, whether traditional mail, electronic delivery to shareholders who have consented to receive communications electronically, or posting on the corporation's website in compliance with notice and access rules. Verify that the distribution method complies with both state corporate law requirements and any federal securities law obligations, and maintain records of the distribution to demonstrate compliance with notice requirements if meeting actions are later challenged.\n\n## Final Deliverable Specifications\n\nThe completed Notice of Annual Shareholders Meeting must be a formal, professionally formatted document that can withstand legal scrutiny and serve as evidence of proper notice if the validity of meeting actions is questioned. The document should employ clear, precise language that avoids ambiguity while maintaining appropriate legal formality and corporate tone. Every date, time, location detail, and procedural instruction must be accurate and internally consistent throughout the document. The notice must be comprehensive enough to satisfy all statutory content requirements while remaining concise enough that shareholders will actually read and understand their rights and obligations. Format the document with clear headings, adequate white space, and professional typography that reflects the corporation's brand standards while ensuring readability. The final notice should be capable of standing alone as legally sufficient notice that protects the validity of all actions taken at the annual meeting and demonstrates the corporation's commitment to transparent corporate governance and shareholder engagement.",
